section.example:
slope to point-slope to slope intercept Notice that the definition m=\dfrac{y_1 − y_0}{x_1 − x_0}
gives us all we need to derive both point-slope form and slope-intercept form. Let our point be (x_0,y_0) and instead of (x_1,y_1), choose (x,y) to be any other point on the line.
\begin{aligned}[t] m \amp =\dfrac{y − y_0}{x − x_0}\\ m(x-x_0) \amp =\dfrac{y − y_0}{\cancel{x − x_0}}\cancel{(x-x_0)}\\ m(x-x_0) \amp = y − y_0\\ y_0 + m(x-x_0) \amp = y\\ y \amp = y_0 + m(x-x_0) \end{aligned}
